.TH 1985 1 "June 2026" "1985 0.4.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
1985 \- Amstrad PCW 8256/8512/9512 emulator
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B 1985
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B 1985
is an Amstrad PCW emulator written in C with SDL3, a sibling project to
1984 (the Amstrad CPC emulator) sharing build system, F9 overlay, and
Z80 core. The PCW family ran CP/M Plus on a Z80 with a custom ASIC
driving a 720x256 monochrome roller-RAM display, an NEC uPD765A floppy
controller, and up to 2 MB of banked RAM.
.PP
Models supported:
.B PCW 8256
(256 KB, single floppy, green monitor),
.B PCW 8512
(512 KB, two floppies, green),
.B PCW 9512
(512 KB, two floppies, white).
.PP
On first run
.B 1985
creates
.IR ~/.config/1985/1985.conf
with sensible defaults; edit it directly or use the F9 overlay.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI --config= PATH
Read configuration from
.I PATH
instead of
.IR ~/.config/1985/1985.conf .
.TP
.BI --memory= KB
RAM size in kilobytes: 256, 512 or 2048 (overrides config).
.TP
.BI --disk-a= PATH
Mount a .dsk image in drive A.
.TP
.BI --disk-b= PATH
Mount a .dsk image in drive B.
.TP
.BI --paste= TEXT
Type TEXT verbatim after boot.
.TP
.BI --load-sna= PATH
Load a .sna snapshot at init.
.TP
.BI --save-sna-at= N:PATH
Save .sna at frame N.
.TP
.BI --screenshot-at= N:PATH
Save a PPM screenshot at frame N and exit.
.TP
.BI --gif-out= PATH
Record GIF from boot to PATH (pair with --exit-after).
.TP
.BI --exit-after= N
Quit after frame N.
.TP
.B --monitor-pty
Open a PTY for the F8 memory monitor.
.TP
.B --kbd-pty
Open a PTY that injects writes as keystrokes.
.TP
.BI --symbols= PATH
Load an SDCC .map for the F8 disassembler.
.TP
.B --web[=PORT]
Start the
.B Web Service
(default port 1985): a self-contained multi-session HTTP daemon, distinct
from the single-shared-machine Web GUI described below. Every distinct
browser (cookie jar) gets its
.B own, fully isolated PCW instance
automatically on first visit \(em live emulator screen (a multipart GIF
stream), full input capture (click the screen to capture keyboard and
mouse, pointer lock, same
.B Ctrl+Enter
release as the emulator window), paste-text and reset controls, per-drive
.B .dsk
upload, and a per-session
.B "Load session config\&..."
control that uploads a
.B 1985.conf
to rebuild just that session. Sessions always boot from clean defaults,
never the host user's real configuration file. Capped at 4 concurrent
sessions; one with no attached viewer for 10 minutes is destroyed to free
the slot; a 5th concurrent session gets a "busy" page instead. The server
binds
.B 0.0.0.0
and has
.BR "no authentication" :
anyone on the local network can create a session and watch/type into it.
Session isolation means a new browser gets a new
.IR machine ,
not new
.IR credentials .
Only enable it on networks you trust.
.B --web
implies
.BR --headless :
no window appears on the host and the browser is the only interface.
.TP
.B "Web GUI (Advanced overlay tab / " web_gui "=true in the config file)"
A separate, simpler HTTP server mirroring the
.B one currently running machine
to every connected browser \(em screen-sharing, not per-session isolation.
Same video and input capture as the Web Service above, minus disk/config
upload and session routing. Starting it from the overlay or the
config key leaves the host window visible; settings persist as
.B web_gui
and
.B web_port
in the configuration file.
.TP
.B --headless
No window on the host: force SDL's
.B offscreen
video driver and
.B dummy
audio driver. Implied by
.BR --web .
A ready-made systemd system unit is installed as
.BR 1985-web.service :
.IP
.nf
systemctl enable --now 1985-web
.fi
.IP
It runs
.B 1985 --web
as a dedicated, shell-less
.B emulator
system account (created automatically via sysusers, shared with 1984's
equivalent unit if both packages are installed) rather than root or an
interactive login user, with systemd sandboxing
.RB ( ProtectSystem=strict ,
.BR NoNewPrivileges ,
no capabilities, ...) on top. It can be customised with a drop-in
.RB ( "systemctl edit 1985-web" );
its config file lives at
.IR /var/lib/emulator/.config/1985/1985.conf .
.TP
.BR -h ", " --help
Show help and exit.
.SH KEYBOARD SHORTCUTS
.TP
.B F4
Save .ppm screenshot.
.TP
.B F5
Warm reset.
.TP
.B F6
Toggle GIF capture.
.TP
.B F8
Open / close memory monitor.
.TP
.B F9
Open options overlay.
.TP
.B F11
Toggle fullscreen.
.TP
.B F12
Quit.
.TP
.B Shift+F1..F8
PCW f1..f8 keys.
.TP
.B Ctrl++ / Ctrl+-
Step window scale 1x .. 4x.
.TP
.B Ctrl+V
Paste clipboard.
.TP
.B Click in window
Capture relative host-mouse input when Input Device is Mouse.
.TP
.B Ctrl+Enter
Release captured mouse input.
.SH OVERLAY
Four tabs:
.B General
(model, RAM, Second drive on 8256, PCW Backplane, Tinker),
.B Media
(drive A / B file pickers),
.B Extensions
(serial port, PerryFi, DK'tronics sound, Input Device: Mouse/Joystick \(em
appears only when the PCW Backplane is plugged in),
.B Advanced
(smoothing, tint, tint mode, video mode, AMX/Kempston mouse type,
DKsound/Atari joystick type, printer mode/model, debug toggles,
serial mode, snapshot save/load).
The Advanced tab is hidden unless
.B tinker=true
is set in the config (toggle it from General).
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.config/1985/1985.conf
Configuration file.
